{"actual_usd":0.15914499999999998,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":225,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"I think the honest answer is: less than people sometimes imagine, and more.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the light is catching on a bucket chain.* \"A camera would've seen a stone already moved, a tomb open, grave clothes left behind, women arriving in shock, angels if the camera could bear that kind of thing, guards undone with fear, and later—Jesus Himself, alive again, talking, walking, eating, being touched.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench a second, thinking how to keep this plain.* \"What it would not have captured, probably, is the actual instant of resurrection. Scripture never really stages that like a spectacle. It gives you the witnesses after: the empty tomb, the messengers, the appearances, the terrified and then overjoyed disciples, and a whole lot of people whose lives stopped making sense unless He had truly risen.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can do the next step and give you the most literal camera-timeline I think the Gospels support—just the sequence, no churchy varnish.\"","rolling_24h_usd":65.44115999999998,"run_id":"e4623c5c-c5ba-4e85-8991-3aa85765fad5"}
